345,http://www.armslist.com/posts/1792345,"For Sale:  COMMANDER""-SIZE .45 ACP PISTOLS","Lexington, Lexington, Kentucky",$ 600,"Listed On: Saturday, June 22, 2013",Handguns,no type,45 ACP                                                                                ,Single Shot                                                                                ,Pistol,"By August of 1983, Randall expanded its line of pistols to include the Service Model-C configuration. The ""C"" stood for compact. Initially, these handguns were even roll-marked ""Service Model-C."" However, in the beginning of 1984, the company decided to give the guns a new identity, and dubbed this configuration as the ""Raider,"" so-named for General Randall's unit which had been known as Randall's Raiders.

Introduced August 31, 1983, the first in the Service Model-C series was the A211, which featured a round-top slide and fixed sights. Barrel length was 4.25-inches, making the over-all length .75-inch less than the standard A111. Magazine capacity (7) and height remained the same. Weight of the A211 was 36 ounces, compared to 38 ounces for the full-sized Model A111. After 992 of the Model A211 pistols were made, production of that model ceased on September 6, 1984. The serial number range went from RF02001C through RF05808C."

Stock Configuration & Condition: The grips are plastic imitation stag similar to old Ajax grips. They’re marked “20” and “K FRAME COMBAT MASTERPIECE / 38 M & P / K-22/K-38 / MED. FRAME SQUARE BUTT”. The right grip panel has a silver colored crest for engraving. Both grip panels show handling marks but no chips or cracks. The grips rate in about Very Good overall condition.
Type of Finish: Nickel
Finish Originality: Probably Not
Bore Condition: The bore is bright and the rifling is shallow. There is no erosion in the bore.

Overall Condition: This handgun retains about 85% of its metal finish. The balance shows a discoloration of the nickel and some pinprick surface erosion. Please see the photos. There is some rust on the unpolished sides of the grip frame, visible only when the grip panels are removed. The screw heads are reasonably sharp. The screw head that retains the cylinder latch is blue. The markings are clear. The hammer is checkered and the trigger is serrated. Overall, this handgun rates in about Good to Very Good condition.
Mechanics: The action functions correctly. This is a four screw, Square Butt “K” Frame revolver with a pinned barrel, service hammer and trigger. We did not fire this handgun.

Box, Paperwork & Accessories: A blue two piece S&W box with metal reinforced corners is provided. It is marked “SMITH & WESSON / .38 MILITARY & POLICE / BLUE FINISH MODEL 10 / 4-INCH HEAVY BARREL” on the end, which correctly describes this revolver. The bottom of the box is marked by hand, in white “571933”. The top is marked with the S&W logo, address and a silver rectangle. The box is missing 20% of its finish and has a tear in one corner. The box is in Poor overall condition.

Assessment: We believe this revolver left the factory “blue” and was later nickeled. At the time this revolver was produced, guns that left the factory nickeled were shipped in Gray boxes, not blue and guns sent to the factory to be nickeled were marked to note that fact. The nickel plating has frosted in a somewhat irregular pattern. The revolver is in Fine mechanical condition and would make a great handgun for home defense."

A refinement of a design created for several European police agencies, the P2000 US uses the trigger system introduced in 2001 on the USP Compact LEM (Law Enforcement Modification) model.

This unique pre-cocked hammer system combines the advantages of a cocked striker component (constant level of trigger pull and short trigger travel from first to last round fired) with a double action hammer system. The P2000 trigger pull has been reduced to 7.3-8.5 pounds of pressure, compared to 12-15 pounds found on many conventional double action pistols.
